properties.name: Carlos Marcelo Payaguaje and Obdulia Payaguaje
Benancio Chimbo Grefa and Tamara Tanguy
Gonzalo Criollo
properties.story_excerpt: Gonzálo Criollo is the son of renowned Cofán shaman Rufino Criollo, and brother of Cofán musicians Silverio and Claus Criollo. Culture and arts run in his family, but Gonzalo has chosen another path: working with his hands. As a senior technician, Gonzálo brings tremendous support to ClearWater.

properties.name: Ocata Nihua
properties.story_excerpt: Accompanying Mitch Anderson, former Amazon Watch corporate accountability director and the current international director for the ClearWater project, on a trip to Yawepare to install 13 rain catchment systems in the community, three of which would be installed in the neighboring community of Nampa Eno.

properties.name: Celio Piaguaje and Irma Yiyocuro
properties.story_excerpt: Meet Celio Piaguaje, Siona technician from the community Sototsiayá. At age 40, Celio stands as one of the most experienced workers in the group. Dedicated to agriculture his entire life, Celio truly knows the meaning of hard work. Every day during construction, Celio takes a 45 minute ride on his dugout canoe to be a part of the ClearWater project.

properties.name: Guillermo Grefa and Lydia Aguinda
properties.story_excerpt: The Kichwa community of Rumipamba has been at the epicenter of Texaco’s contamination and the 20-year legal battle to bring the company to justice. In the meantime, community members are taking steps to improve the health situation in Rumipamba.

properties.name: Salome Chuquitarco and José Tanguila Grefa
properties.story_excerpt: Unlike the majority of Rumipamba’s founding community members, Salome did not move to the area from one of the Kichwa communities near Tena. She and her husband José and their children moved from the highland city of Latacunga over 30 years ago.

properties.name: Moipa Nihua and Guillermina Ana Gaba Caiga
properties.story_excerpt: Ocata and Moipa are father and son, members of the Waorani Nationality. In many ways they embody the contemporary story of the Waorani: a strong and proud hunting culture that controlled the largest territory of Ecuador’s Amazonian peoples.

properties.name: Celestino Piaguaje
properties.story_excerpt: Celestino Piaguaje is a special figure among the Secoya. His life mission has been to bridge Secoya tradition with modern Western thought, to integrate Secoya spiritual belief with the teachings of the Bible.

properties.name: Rogelio Piaguaje
properties.story_excerpt: Rogelio Payaguaje lives in the Secoya community of San Pablo. He has three daughters and many grandchildren. Rogelio is in his mid-seventies, and like all Secoya his age he is still very active, as life in the forest requires. Every day he fishes, collects fruit, and works in his garden.

properties.name: Fabian Umenda and Lola Criollo
properties.story_excerpt: As ClearWater coordinator for Sinangüe, Fabian was present for every stage in the installation of rain catchment systems in his community; helping to transport materials by canoe to houses along the river and informing the Nationalities Coordinator if materials or tools were missing. Thanks to Fabian’s hard work, the installation of 24 rainwater systems was a smooth process.

properties.name: Calisto Umenda and Delia Quenama
properties.story_excerpt: The Cofán community of Sinangüe is located in the tropical foothills of the Andes Mountains. Just beyond, the landscape levels out into the seemingly infinite Western Amazon Basin. This is the ancestral homeland of the Cofán people. They have lived here in these mountain forests for hundreds, if not thousands of years.

properties.name: Fredy Queta and Tsenene Criollo
properties.story_title: A Trip Up the Pisorie River
properties.story_excerpt: A journey up the Pissorie River with the Cofán of Ukavati.

properties.name: Hugo Payaguaje and Flor Tanguy
properties.story_excerpt: Hugo, from the community of Aboquehuira, is president of the Siona federation, a teacher, and ClearWater coordinator for the Siona nationality.
